⊕meta⊕
name = "annotate-sky-workflow"
description = "Insert inline ※※ rationale comments before each node in a .sky file explaining the node's purpose and the meaning of its when/chain_from/depends_on edges, then lint until clean."
trigger.manual = true
output_style = "terse"
max_budget_usd = 3
⊕⊕

§read§
bash_file = "./scripts/read.sh"
§§

§annotate§
model = "sonnet"
skills = ["sky-workflow-authoring"]
depends_on = ["read"]
trigger_rule = "all_success"
§§

∆annotate∆
Annotate the workflow file {{dir}}/{{name}}.sky with inline rationale comments.

Steps:
1. READ {{dir}}/{{name}}.sky in full.
2. For each §id§ node-config block, add a concise ※<id>※ ... ※※ comment block IMMEDIATELY BEFORE that §id§ opener line. The id in the opener must match the node id exactly. The comment must explain:
   - the node's purpose (what it does in one line),
   - the meaning of each edge it has: depends_on (which upstreams must finish first), trigger_rule (when this node runs relative to those upstreams: all_done / all_success / one_success / one_failure), chain_from (which prior Claude session it resumes), and any when condition (the exact data condition that must hold).
3. Use the Edit tool for every change. Do NOT use bash/sed to rewrite delimiter lines; that is fragile and will corrupt the file.
4. PRESERVE every node, every trigger, every ∆ prompt body, and the ⊕meta⊕ block exactly. Do not rename ids, reorder nodes, change bash, or alter any prompt text. Only insert ※<id>※ comment blocks.
5. Keep each comment terse and machine-oriented. Skip a node only if an identical ※<id>※ rationale already precedes it.

Each step-associated doc block: opener ※<id>※ alone on its line (where <id> is the node id), closer ※※ alone on its line, body in between.
∆∆

§lint§
model = "sonnet"
skills = ["sky-workflow-authoring"]
depends_on = ["annotate"]
trigger_rule = "all_success"
loop.until.bash = "sky lint \"$SKY_DIR/$SKY_NAME.sky\""
loop.max = 6
§§

∆lint∆
Run `sky lint "$SKY_DIR/$SKY_NAME.sky"` on the freshly annotated file (the loop re-runs this until lint exits 0, up to the cap).

If lint reports any error or warning:
- READ {{dir}}/{{name}}.sky again.
- Fix ONLY the problems lint names — most likely a malformed ※※ block from the annotate step (an opener or closer not alone on its line, or an unbalanced ※※ pair).
- Apply fixes with the Edit tool. Never delete a node, trigger, edge, or prompt body to satisfy the linter.

If lint already passes, make no edits.
∆∆

※※
annotate-sky-workflow — add inline rationale comments to one .sky, then lint clean.

Inserts a ※※ comment block before each §id§ node documenting the node's
purpose and what its depends_on / trigger_rule / chain_from / when edges mean.
Best for COMPLEX workflows whose edges are non-obvious. A small, terse library
file may not want the extra verbosity — annotation adds line count.

DAG:
  read ──▶ annotate ──▶ lint
  (bash:      (sonnet:        (sonnet loop:
   verify      Edit in           sky lint until 0,
   file        place)            max 6 passes)
   exists)

  Edges:
    read     all_success gate is implicit (bash; nonzero exit if file missing).
    annotate trigger_rule=all_success  → runs only if read found the file.
    lint     trigger_rule=all_success  → runs only if annotate succeeded;
             loop.until.bash re-runs the node until `sky lint` exits 0.

Run:
  sky run annotate-sky-workflow --vars dir=.sky/workflows,name=triage-issue

Vars:
  dir   directory holding the target .sky (e.g. .sky/workflows). → $SKY_DIR
  name  workflow filename WITHOUT the .sky extension.            → $SKY_NAME

The target file edited in place is "$dir/$name.sky".
※※

※read※
Verify the target .sky exists; exit 1 if missing so downstream
all_success gates skip cleanly. Reports node-config block count for context.
※※

※annotate※
Sonnet w/ sky-workflow-authoring skill. Reads the file and
inserts a ※<id>※ rationale block before each §id§ via the Edit tool. Preserves
every node/trigger/prompt exactly. Gated all_success on read.
※※

※lint※
Sonnet loop. loop.until.bash runs `sky lint` on the file each
pass and stops at exit 0 (max 6). Fixes only lint-named issues (typically a
malformed ※※ block) with Edit; never strips structure. Gated all_success on
annotate.
※※
